Title = {{Big concerns with small projects: Evaluating the socio-ecological
   impacts of small hydropower projects in India}},
Journal = {{AMBIO}},
Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{46}},
Number = {{4}},
Pages = {{500-511}},
Month = {{MAY}},
Abstract = {{Although Small Hydropower Projects (SHPs) are encouraged as sources of
   clean and green energy, there is a paucity of research examining their
   socio-ecological impacts. We assessed the perceived socio-ecological
   impacts of 4 SHPs within the Western Ghats in India by conducting
   semi-structured interviews with local respondents. Primary interview
   data were sequentially validated with secondary data, and respondent
   perceptions were subsequently compared against the expected baseline of
   assured impacts. We evaluated the level of awareness about SHPs, their
   perceived socio-economic impacts, influence on resource access and
   impacts on human-elephant interactions. The general level of awareness
   about SHPs was low, and assurances of local electricity and employment
   generation remained largely unfulfilled. Additionally most respondents
   faced numerous unanticipated adverse impacts. We found a strong
   relationship between SHP construction and increasing levels of
   human-elephant conflict. Based on the disparity between assured and
   actual social impacts, we suggest that policies regarding SHPs be
   suitably revised.}},
