Title = {{Sustainable and economical small-scale and low-head hydropower
   generation: A promising alternative potential solution for energy
   generation at local and regional scale}},
Journal = {{APPLIED ENERGY}},
Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{188}},
Pages = {{378-391}},
Month = {{FEB 15}},
Abstract = {{Accounting for more than 16\% of the world's net electricity production,
   hydropower is one of the most commonly used renewable sources of energy.
   Small-scale hydropower (SSH) systems are becoming increasingly
   successful options for hydropower generation, particularly in small
   localities and remote areas. Regardless of its low capacity, small-scale
   hydropower produces cheap, clean, and reliable electricity. The
   objective of this study is to provide a sustainable and economical
   solution for the increasing demand of electricity through small-scale
   hydropower generation in Pakistan. River flow and low head potential
   were investigated at twenty sites along the Upper Swat Canal and Swat
   River for hydropower generation. The sites were selected based on large
   differential head, velocity, ease of access, close proximity to dense
   population, and structural support. Hydropower capacity was calculated
   for each site based on the collected flow and hydraulic data. The cost
   per kWh of energy generated has been estimated by dividing the average
   annual recurring cost with annual generation over the lifetime of the
   project. Cost analysis indicated that purchasing one unit at 0.04 US\$
   is suitable for both the consumer and the government. Results revealed
   that each site is qualified to provide stable energy to more than 1500
   houses based on the maximum consumption per home. The cost of the
   proposed power system was identified as the incentive factor in this
   study. In addition to the minimal variation in the seasonal production,
   the studied sites produced as much as 21\% of the total Swat River
   production. The proposed spatial power distribution scenarios have
   contributed a potentially flexible alternative and cost-effective
   solution to the proposed SSH system. (C) 2016 Elsevier Ltd. All rights
   reserved.}},
