Abstract = {{Climate changes are likely to be significantly affected by
   reservoirs/lakes due to emission of greenhouse gas (GHG), change in the
   magnitude and seasonality of river runoffs and severe extreme events. In
   this study, a coupled GHG Risk Assessment Tool (GRAT) and Soil Water
   Assessment Tool (SWAT) are used to predict the GHG risk of Koteshwar
   reservoirs located in Uttarakhand, India. Before running the GRAT model,
   SWAT model was used to simulate the runoffs (one of the major input of
   GRAT). The model was calibrated (2004-09) and validated (2010-13) at
   Uttarkashi station using monthly discharge data. The model performance
   was checked by R-2, NSE, RSR, and p-value as 0.785, 0.60, 0.63, and
   0.04, respectively, during calibration and 0.790, 0.66, 0.57, and 0.06
   during validation and shows satisfactory model performance on monthly
   time step. Further, GRAT model is also applied and the results show that
   Koteshwar reservoir is found to be under high risk of CO2 (CO2 > 645mg
   m(-2) d(-1)) and medium risk of CH4 (CH4 < 45mg m(-2) d(-1)) till 2023.
   Subsequently, the GHG risk is minimized after passage of time over
   100years. These models may be used by the policy-makers to know the
   potential of GHG and its vulnerability to the reservoirs after the
   impoundment.}},
